CHD Classification

1. Introduction

The goal of this project is to apply various machine learning techniques to a medical dataset to achieve the most accurate prediction of CHD risk possible. I will compare different classification models and identify the most predictive factors.

The notebook runs through in one go in a few seconds, provided the installation (next cell) has been performed correctly.

The following packages need to be installed:

conda install scikit-learn conda-forge::umap-learn seaborn numpy=1.26.4
  • scikit-learn as base package for ML
  • umap-learn as extension of scikit for UMAP dimension reduction
  • seaborn for better visualizations
  • numpy=1.26.4 as fix for incompatibility between umap-learn and scikit-learn (Breaking-Change in numpy 2.0)

4. Machine Learning Model Evaluation

4.1 Data Preparation

I clean the data and prepare it for further analysis.

Cholesterol values of 0 are likely incomplete data. I need to treat these differently and replace them. I choose - if available - a suitable comparison group in my dataset. Otherwise the median.

In[6]:
# Median of cholesterol values for normal values
median_chol = data[data["Chol"] > 0]["Chol"].median()

# Create binary indicator to possibly better track the distribution of cholesterol values later
data["Chol_was_zero"] = (data["Chol"] == 0).astype(int)


def impute_chol(row):
    if row["Chol"] > 0:
        return row["Chol"]

    # Select similar patients (same gender, similar age)
    similar = data[
        (data["Gender"] == row["Gender"])
        & (abs(data["Age"] - row["Age"]) < 5)
        & (data["Chol"] > 0)
    ]

    if len(similar) > 0:
        return similar["Chol"].median()
    else:
        return median_chol


# Apply imputation
data["Chol"] = data.apply(impute_chol, axis=1)

There exists one value with BloodPressure = 0. Since there's only one entry, I decide to remove it.

In[7]:
data = data[data["BloodPressure"] != 0]
Encodings for categorical or non-numerical values

In this cell I encode the categorical variables "Gender", "AP" and "ECG". For "Gender" and "AP" I use LabelEncoder, since these variables each contain only two categories. By using LabelEncoder I save myself one additional column each, which would arise with One-Hot-Encoding. Probably negligible performance gain, but maximally efficient.

For the variable "ECG", which has more than two categories, I use One-Hot-Encoding to transform each category into a separate column. This enables a clear and unambiguous representation of the different categories of "ECG".

In[8]:
# Encode categorical variables
le_gender = LabelEncoder()
le_ap = LabelEncoder()

data["Gender_encoded"] = le_gender.fit_transform(data["Gender"])
data["AP_encoded"] = le_ap.fit_transform(data["AP"])

# One-Hot-Encoding instead of LabelEncoder
ecg_dummies = pd.get_dummies(data["ECG"], prefix="ECG", dtype=int)
data = pd.concat([data, ecg_dummies], axis=1)

# Display mapping of encoded values
print("\nEncoding for Gender:")
for i, category in enumerate(le_gender.classes_):
    print(f"{category}: {i}")

print("\nEncoding for AP:")
for i, category in enumerate(le_ap.classes_):
    print(f"{category}: {i}")

print("\nEncoding for ECG:")
for i, col in enumerate(ecg_dummies.columns):
    print(f"{col}: 1 if ECG = '{col.split('_')[1]}', otherwise 0")

4.4 Dimension Reduction and Visualization

4.4.1 PCA (Principal Component Analysis)

In[13]:
# Standardize data for PCA
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_data)

# Apply PCA
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)

# Visualize PCA results
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
scatter = plt.scatter(X_pca[:, 0], X_pca[:, 1], c=y_data, cmap="viridis", alpha=0.8)
plt.title("PCA: 2D Projection of Data")
plt.xlabel(f"PC1 (Explains {pca.explained_variance_ratio_[0]:.2%} of variance)")
plt.ylabel(f"PC2 (Explains {pca.explained_variance_ratio_[1]:.2%} of variance)")
plt.colorbar(scatter, label="CHD Class")
plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
plt.show()

# Feature contributions to the first two principal components
component_names = ["PC1", "PC2"]
feature_names = X_data.columns
pca_components = pd.DataFrame(
    pca.components_, columns=feature_names, index=component_names
)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.heatmap(pca_components, annot=True, cmap="coolwarm", fmt=".2f")
plt.title("Feature Contributions to PCA Components")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

4.5.1 Model Results

The initial evaluation of my seven classification models shows clear performance differences:

  1. The Support Vector Machine (SVM) achieves the best results with an accuracy of 0.8391 and an F1-score of 0.8582 on the test set, followed by K-Nearest Neighbors (Accuracy: 0.8304, F1: 0.8458) and Logistic Regression (Accuracy: 0.8261, F1: 0.8413).
  2. Interestingly, Logistic Regression shows the highest Cross-Validation score with 0.7731 0.0195, indicating particularly robust generalization ability.
  3. The Decision Tree performs worst with an accuracy of 0.7435 and an F1-score of 0.7611.

The observed discrepancy between test and cross-validation scores for some models indicates a certain degree of overfitting. Based on these results, I will select SVM, KNN and Logistic Regression (the 3 best models) for further analysis and optimization.

4.5.2 Detailed Analysis of Best Models

In[20]:
best_models = {
    "Support Vector Machine": models["Support Vector Machine"],
    "K-Nearest Neighbors": models["K-Nearest Neighbors"],
    "Logistic Regression": models["Logistic Regression"],
}

Based on my first evaluation, I found that SVM, K-Nearest Neighbors and Logistic Regression are among the most powerful models. Now I want to analyze these three models in more detail to get a better understanding of their strengths and weaknesses.

I will investigate the following aspects:

  1. Confusion matrices of the models
  2. ROC curves and AUC values
  3. Distribution of prediction probabilities

These analyses will help me understand how the models make decisions and where they have difficulties.

In[21]:
# Confusion matrices for the best models
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(18, 5))

for i, (name, model) in enumerate(best_models.items()):
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)

    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", ax=axes[i])
    axes[i].set_title(f"Confusion Matrix: {name}")
    axes[i].set_xlabel("Predicted Class")
    axes[i].set_ylabel("True Class")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
Confusion Matrices:

  • Support Vector Machine: Shows strong recognition performance for CHD-positive cases (112 TP), but has more False Positives (22 FP) than the other models. The SVM seems to tend to classify patients as CHD-positive, leading to high sensitivity (88.2%) at the cost of specificity (78.6%).

  • K-Nearest Neighbors: Offers more balanced performance with better recognition of negative cases (84 TN) compared to SVM, but shows more False Negatives (20 FN). KNN has lower sensitivity (84.3%), but higher specificity (81.6%).

  • Logistic Regression: Behaves similarly to KNN with identical specificity (81.6%), but has slightly more False Negatives (21 FN), resulting in slightly lower sensitivity (83.5%).

In[22]:
# ROC curves for the best models
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

for name, model in best_models.items():
    # model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
    y_pred_proba = model.predict_proba(X_test_scaled)[:, 1]

    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_proba)
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)

    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=f"{name} (AUC = {roc_auc:.3f})")

plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], "k--", label="Random Prediction")
plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate")
plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate")
plt.title("ROC Curves of Best Models")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
plt.show()
ROC Curves:

The ROC curves and AUC values provide insight into the overall discriminative ability of the models:

  • Logistic Regression shows the best overall performance with an AUC of 0.894
  • SVM follows closely with an AUC of 0.882
  • KNN shows the lowest, but still very solid value with an AUC of 0.845

All models significantly outperform random prediction, with logistic regression being particularly superior in the middle range of the curve, indicating a good balance between sensitivity and specificity.

In[23]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

for name, model in best_models.items():
    # model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
    y_pred_proba = model.predict_proba(X_test_scaled)[:, 1]

    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_test, y_pred_proba)
    pr_auc = auc(recall, precision)

    plt.plot(recall, precision, label=f"{name} (AUC = {pr_auc:.3f})")

plt.xlabel("Recall")
plt.ylabel("Precision")
plt.title("Precision-Recall Curves of Best Models")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
plt.show()
Precision-Recall Curves:

When considering Precision and Recall, especially important for unbalanced data:

  • Logistic Regression dominates with the highest AUC (0.923) and shows excellent precision values particularly in the middle recall range (0.4-0.7)
  • SVM (AUC = 0.901) shows stronger fluctuations in precision, but maintains good values even at higher recall
  • KNN (AUC = 0.868) drops more quickly especially in the high recall range
Conclusion:

Logistic regression offers the best balance across all metrics, particularly for a medical context where both false positive and false negative results can be critical. SVM could be preferred if higher sensitivity is more important (e.g., for screening purposes), while KNN shows the most stable performance in correctly identifying non-CHD cases.

The hyperparameter optimization shows interesting results for my three best models:

In[29]:
# Here I could perform an aggregation of top features from all models
from sklearn.inspection import permutation_importance


all_importances = []

for name, model in optimized_models.items():
    model_clone = clone(model)
    model_clone.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)

    # Calculate Permutation Importance
    result = permutation_importance(
        model_clone, X_test_scaled, y_test, n_repeats=10, random_state=42, n_jobs=-1
    )

    # Add results to list
    importance_df = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Feature": X_data.columns,
            "Importance": result.importances_mean,
            "Model": name,
        }
    )
    all_importances.append(importance_df)

# Combine all importance values
combined_importance = pd.concat(all_importances)

# Calculate average rank of each feature across all models
avg_rank = combined_importance.groupby("Feature")["Importance"].mean().reset_index()
avg_rank = avg_rank.sort_values("Importance", ascending=False)

# Visualize average importance
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.barplot(x="Importance", y="Feature", data=avg_rank)
plt.title("Average Feature Importance Across All Models")
plt.xlabel("Average Importance")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The Feature Importance analysis shows that AP (Angina Pectoris) is the strongest predictor for CHD, followed by RZ, BloodSugar and maximum heart rate.

These insights have direct clinical relevance as they align with known risk factors and symptoms. The high importance of AP confirms that this symptom is a strong indicator for the presence of CHD. It's also notable that especially the ECG class "ST" seems to be the most relevant ECG class.

The results suggest that an effective screening tool for CHD should prioritize these main features, with classical risk factors like cholesterol and blood pressure appearing less discriminative than the symptomatic indicators.

4.6.2 Feature Engineering

Based on the Feature Importance analysis, I can now perform targeted feature engineering to further improve model performance.

The most important features based on my previous analysis
In[30]:
top_features = list(avg_rank["Feature"].head(5))
print(f"Top 5 selected features for Feature Engineering: {top_features}")

Top 5 selected features for Feature Engineering: ['AP_encoded', 'RZ', 'BloodSugar', 'HFmax', 'Gender_encoded']
Various Feature Engineering Strategies

  1. Top Features Only: This strategy reduces the dataset to the five most important features based on the previous Feature Importance analysis. It serves to minimize noise and reduce model complexity by removing less informative features.

  2. Polynomial Features: Here, nonlinear relationships are captured by creating quadratic terms (e.g., Age) and cross products (e.g., Age BloodPressure) from the top-5 features. This allows the model to recognize more complex, nonlinear relationships, even if the base algorithm is linear.

  3. Interaction Terms: This strategy keeps all original features and adds targeted interactions between medically relevant parameters. For example, "Age_BloodPressure" captures the combined effect of these two risk factors, which is particularly valuable for Logistic Regression since it doesn't naturally model interactions.

  4. PCA Transformation: This dimensionality reduction technique projects the data onto five orthogonal principal components that capture maximum variance. This can reduce noise and eliminate multicollinearity, but loses direct interpretability of features.

  5. Feature Selection (SelectKBest): In contrast to manual selection of top features, this method uses the statistical F-test to identify the five features with the strongest univariate relationship to the target class (CHD). It's less subjective than manual selection, but doesn't consider interactions between features.

In[31]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest, f_classif

engineering_strategies = {
    "Top Features Only": {
        "description": "Use only the top-5 most important features",
        "transform": lambda X: X[top_features],
    },
    "Polynomial Features": {
        "description": "Generate polynomial features (degree 2) from top features",
        "transform": lambda X: pd.DataFrame(
            PolynomialFeatures(degree=2, include_bias=False).fit_transform(
                X[top_features]
            ),
            # Generic column names that safely match the feature count
            columns=[
                f"poly_{i}"
                for i in range(
                    PolynomialFeatures(degree=2, include_bias=False)
                    .fit_transform(X[top_features][:1])
                    .shape[1]
                )
            ],
        ),
    },
    "Interaction Terms": {
        "description": "Add interaction terms between important numerical features",
        "transform": lambda X: pd.concat(
            [
                X,  # Keep original features
                pd.DataFrame(
                    {
                        "Age_BloodPressure": X["Age"] * X["BloodPressure"] / 100,
                        "Age_Chol": X["Age"] * X["Chol"] / 100,
                        "BloodPressure_HFmax": X["BloodPressure"] * X["HFmax"] / 100,
                        "Age_HFmax": X["Age"] * X["HFmax"] / 100,
                        "Chol_BloodSugar": X["Chol"] * X["BloodSugar"] / 100,
                    }
                ),
            ],
            axis=1,
        ),
    },
    "PCA Transformation": {
        "description": "Use the first 5 PCA components",
        "transform": lambda X: pd.DataFrame(
            PCA(n_components=5).fit_transform(StandardScaler().fit_transform(X)),
            columns=[f"PC{i+1}" for i in range(5)],
        ),
    },
    "Feature Selection (SelectKBest)": {
        "description": "Select the best k (=5) features using univariate statistics",
        "transform": lambda X: pd.DataFrame(
            SelectKBest(f_classif, k=5).fit_transform(X, y_data),
            columns=[
                X.columns[i]
                for i in SelectKBest(f_classif, k=5)
                .fit(X, y_data)
                .get_support(indices=True)
            ],
        ),
    },
}

# Convert results to DataFrame for easier plotting
from helpers.feature_engineering import test_feature_engineering_strategies


results_df = []
for model_name, strategies in test_feature_engineering_strategies(
    strategies=engineering_strategies,
    models=optimized_models,
    X_data=X_data,
    y_data=y_data,
).items():
    for strategy_name, f1_score in strategies.items():
        if f1_score is not None:  # Only valid results
            results_df.append(
                {"Model": model_name, "Strategy": strategy_name, "F1-Score": f1_score}
            )
results_df = pd.DataFrame(results_df)

# Create grouped bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))

# Define color palette - "Original" in different color
unique_strategies = results_df["Strategy"].unique()
colors = plt.cm.Blues(np.linspace(0.05, 0.95, len(unique_strategies)))
strategy_colors = {}
for i, strategy in enumerate(unique_strategies):
    if strategy == "Original":
        strategy_colors[strategy] = "black"  # Highlight original strategy
    else:
        strategy_colors[strategy] = colors[i]

# Number of models and bar width
unique_models = results_df["Model"].unique()
n_models = len(unique_models)
width = 0.8 / len(unique_strategies)  # Width of each bar

# X-positions for models
x = np.arange(n_models)

# Plot one bar per model for each strategy
for i, strategy in enumerate(unique_strategies):
    strategy_data = results_df[results_df["Strategy"] == strategy]

    # Ensure data is in correct order
    scores = []
    for model in unique_models:
        model_data = strategy_data[strategy_data["Model"] == model]
        scores.append(model_data["F1-Score"].values[0])

    offset = (i - len(unique_strategies) / 2 + 0.5) * width

    plt.bar(
        x + offset,
        scores,
        width,
        label=strategy,
        color=strategy_colors[strategy],
        edgecolor="black",
        linewidth=0.5,
    )

# Axis labels and layout
plt.xlabel("Model")
plt.ylabel("F1-Score")
plt.title("Comparison of Feature Engineering Strategies for All Models")
plt.xticks(x, unique_models)
plt.legend(title="Feature Engineering Strategy")
plt.grid(axis="y", linestyle="--", alpha=0.7)

# Adjust y-axis to better see small differences
min_score = max(0.6, results_df["F1-Score"].min() - 0.05)
max_score = min(1.0, results_df["F1-Score"].max() + 0.05)
plt.ylim(min_score, max_score)

# Display values above bars
for i, strategy in enumerate(unique_strategies):
    strategy_data = results_df[results_df["Strategy"] == strategy]

    for j, model in enumerate(unique_models):
        model_data = strategy_data[strategy_data["Model"] == model]
        if not model_data.empty:
            score = model_data["F1-Score"].values[0]
            offset = (i - len(unique_strategies) / 2 + 0.5) * width
            plt.text(
                j + offset,
                score + 0.005,
                f"{score:.3f}",
                ha="center",
                va="bottom",
                fontsize=10,
            )

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
Interpretation of Feature Engineering Results

The analysis of the Feature Engineering comparison shows different effects on the three models:

  • For the Support Vector Machine (F1: 0.858), all applied strategies led to deterioration, with interaction terms (F1: 0.845) still performing best.
  • For the K-Nearest Neighbors model (F1: 0.851), the performance drop from feature engineering was even more pronounced, with polynomial features (F1: 0.833) as the best alternative.
  • Particularly interesting is the Logistic Regression, where interaction terms (F1: 0.849) actually achieved improvement over the original (F1: 0.837). This indicates that logistic regression benefits from explicit feature interactions, while more complex models like SVM can already implicitly capture relationships between features.

For all models, PCA transformation and pure feature selection led to the greatest performance losses, suggesting that all captured features contain relevant information for CHD classification.

5. Summary, Conclusions and Outlook

I have implemented and compared various classification models for predicting CHD based on medical parameters. In doing so, I have both optimized the hyperparameters of the models and performed feature engineering.

My analyses have shown that the Support Vector Machine (C=1, gamma=0.1, probability=True) delivers the best results. The most important features for predicting CHD were AP (Angina Pectoris), maximum heart rate, RZ and whether the patient already has a blood sugar disease. These insights could be important in medical practice to identify patients with increased CHD risk early.
